A Future Beyond Example
JERUSALEM – At almost 90 years of age, I can't recall a time when the past was considered so insignificant in political decision-making.
No major developments of the present could have been predicted by anyone.
Experts did study the past, but due to their confinement within old paradigms, they were unable to deduce the future from it.
Given the dynamic complexity of the world today, in which, due to a rapidly changing, science-based global economy, more events are interdependent, it is not possible for us to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation that cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is diminishing. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome because science and technology are borderless.
Global companies operating worldwide want to carry out their business on all continents, resulting in a loss of sovereignty on the one hand, but on the other hand, racism and prejudices as well as nationalism are weakened to a significant extent.
Owing to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation, which is technologically more skilled than its parents and connected with each other through social networks that overcome national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people are also the vanguard of forming political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring", the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street and the protests in Russia mark no battle of cultures, but a clash of generations.
The young generation knows that the way states and economies are currently run is unsuitable for the new times.
However, there are political "freeriders" who want to exploit this latest awakening, but not through the further development of an agenda of freedom, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, primarily Islamist extremists have taken the protests of the young generation for themselves and thereby stolen the revolution from them.
Israel has positively reacted to the will of the young generation, but cannot and must not interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are at heart with the rebellious young people and their legitimate aspiration for freedom and basic rights, which should enable them to make themselves heard, choose their political leadership, and earn their living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their land will no longer be the only democracy in the region, for the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
There is, however, the serious concern that the politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized liberals at elections and thereby prevent peace and stability.
Radikale Fundamentalisten can offer no real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheaval threatens their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, for its success is rooted in the fact that the country initially had absolutely nothing.
When we returned to our homeland, we were rich in history, but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our Human Capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. That's why we today have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We consume less water and yet have higher harvest yields per square meter of cultivation area than any other country in the world.
What Israel can achieve, others can also accomplish.
We are more than willing to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Most of all, we must do everything in our power to bring an end to the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and this is also not Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state, which exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because solving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who aim to manipulate civil movements to promote their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, determined and groundbreaking political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially the Iran is a source of moral depravity, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. It crushes legitimate protests of its own citizens and works against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Also, Iran uses several proxies to instigate terror against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring atomic weapons, its leaders could shake the Middle East and further exacerbate extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But Israel is not the only one threatened. Iran is a threat to peace and stability worldwide.
The democracies of this world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire atomic weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it is too late.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world today.
To a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to exploit their potential.
The teachers of today should motivate our children to creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free speech.
I am writing this article at 88 years old, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create a new and unparalleled world.
The future is already here. Looking back has no sense.
